Final Project¶

Systems & Technologies: Python

The Question / Problem¶

You have been hired as an indepedent auditor by Colorado’s Boulder County Assessors Office to help with the following problems.

Problem 1: Annual Report Insights (50 pts)¶

The Accessors Office is set to release their annual report on the valuation of residential single family properties. They have asked you to explore the data and produce at least 2 key findings they can share in their annual report to the public.

Problem 2: Estimate Home Values (45 pts)¶

The Assessors Office needs help improving their valuation process for residential single family properties. They have asked you to write a KNN alogorithm to value new homes based on similar home sales. By law, residential properties must be valued by using a "market approach". This predicts the price a property would bring on the open market in a transaction between a willing, informed, and knowledgeable buyer and seller. A property can be valued through the process of analyzing comparable sales. A comparable sale is any qualified sale in the last 5 years (January 2015 - December 2020).

The central factors used by the Assessors for property valuation are:

  • Location
  • Living Area (SQFT)
  • Age of the Home
  • Finished Basement

Problem 3: Ethics Review (5 pts)¶

Fairness and accuracy are vitally important. If the assessed values are too high, the property owners will overpay in taxes. If the assessed values are too low then we may fall short of the capital needed to cover the budget approved by legislators. As such, thinking through the impact of how we predict home prices is vitial.

Problem 1: EDA for the Annual Report Insights¶

Goal¶

Perform EDA on the property valuations for "1-Story" and "2-3 Story" single family residential buildings. Identify at least 2 key insights and/or graphs that tell a story about the valuations for these properties for the annual report.

1.0 Get the Data (15 pts)¶

Tasks:

  1. Read in the following data:
    • buildings.csv
    • land.csv
    • values.csv
    • owner_addresses.csv
  2. Adjust the structure of our data as necessary (joins, drop unneeded columns, add features, etc).
  3. Inspect and handle missing values as necessary.

Note: These files have been pre-filtered to only include single family properties. Additionaly, in some tables columns have been dropped before sending you the data (such as owner name in owner_addresses). Complete meta data about each file can be found in the "ar-property-data-download-help.pdf" document.

Part II: Algorithmic Thinking¶

Objective¶

In this portion of the assignment, our goal is to predict the value of a new single-family property given comparable sales data. One way we might estimate the value of a home is to look at the value of k-similar nearby homes that have recently sold. The average sales price of those k homes could then be used as the predicted valuation for our new home. This process is effectively how the K-Nearest Neighbor Algorithm (KNN) works for regression problems.

KNN is considered a supervised machine learning algorithm that can be used to solve both classification and regression problems. As shown above, we can be used to solve nonparametric regression problems such as predicting the price of a new home based on similar nearby homes.

Recall the central factors used for property valuation:

  • Location
  • Living Area (SQFT)
  • Age of the Home
  • Finished Basement

2.0 Read and Prepare the Sales Data (15 pts)¶

Tasks:

  • Load the sales.csv
  • Keep only qualified sales (sales.sales_cd == 'Q') and sales.price > 0.
  • Keep only sales in the last 5 years (01/01/2015 and 12/31/2020)
  • Join "sales" with the necessary data frames to add the following columns
    • nh, this is the neighborhood number that must be used to identify comparable sales by location.
    • totalActualVal
    • builtYear
    • EffectiveYear
    • TotalFinishedSF
    • A boolean flag (1/0) for if the basement is finished that you will need to create

2.1 Property Valuation using KNN (20 pts)¶

Tasks:

  • Complete the below function predict_knn() so that it finds the k-most similar sales properties in the appraisal neighborhood (nh) and returns the average sale price for those k properties as the predicted value (y_hat).

How this problem will be graded:

  • You will not be graded on your prediction accuracy or the value of k you select. You will be graded on how you write your code and, in particular, if you took advantage of vectorization. You must write your own knn function from scratch, do not use sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsRegressor.

KNN Regression Pseudo Code¶

Given a new data point:

  1. Calculate the Euclidean distance between the new data point and all known datapoints in the dataset.
  2. Select the k closest datapoints.
  3. Average the target variable for the k closest data points.

Euclidean Distance formula for 3-dimenstions where p_1 and q_1 is finished_sqft, p2 and q_2 is home_age, and p3 and q_3 is finished_basement:

$$d(p,q)=\sqrt{(p_1-q_1)^2 + (p_2-q_2)^2 + (p_3-q_3)^2}$$

.

In [73]:
def predict_knn(sales_data, k, nh, finished_sqft, home_age, finished_basement):
    
    #error for invalid neighborhood
    if nh not in sales_data.nh.unique():
        raise TypeError("Invalid Neighborhood")
    
    #error for invalue k value
    if k < 3:
        raise TypeError("K must be larger than 3")
        
    #if not isinstance(home_age, (int, float)):
    #    raise TypeError("home_age must be numeric")
        
    #if not isinstance(finished_sqft, (int, float)):
    #    raise TypeError("finished_sqft must be numeric")
        
    #if not isinstance(finished_basement, (int,bool)):
    #    raise TypeError("finished_basement must be T/F or 1/0") 
    
    #if finished_basement > 1:
    #    raise TypeError("finished_basement must be T/F or 1/0")
        
    #if finished_basement < 0:
    #    raise TypeError("finished_basement must be T/F or 1/0")
    
    # Filter down to our sales data to the provided neighborhood number, nh.
    sales_data = sales_data[sales_data.nh == nh]
    
    #Adding 2 to k, will remove two of the outlier properties below
    k = k+2
    
    # Calculate the Euclidean Distance for finished_sqft, home_age, and finished_basement for every sale in our nh.
    knnFilt = np.sqrt(
        (finished_sqft - sales_data.TotalFinishedSF)**2+
        #Weighted basement more heavily otherwise the 1/0 will have no real effect compared to finished sqft or home age
        (finished_basement*10 - sales_data.bsmtFinished*10)**2+
        #Avg-ing Home Age Difference by Built year and Effective Year
        (home_age - (2021 - (sales_data.EffectiveYear+sales_data.builtYear)/2))**2
    ).sort_values().head(k).index  
    
    compared_props = sales_data.loc[knnFilt]
    
    #Removing most and least expensive properties from list to leave k values
    y_hat = compared_props[:-1].tail(-1).totalActualVal.mean().round(2)
    
    return y_hat

Answer¶

One of the major considerations in this data set is differentiating between Price and TotalActualValue. Price being the most accurate representaion of what the market will bring for a given property vs the more subjective valuation of the assessor.

I tried to account for a couple outliers in my KNN function by eliminating the high and low values of the set of properties most closely matching the charactoristics given. I also tried to factor in a bit of the normalization concept by scaling the values of the bsmt finished to an arbitrary value. That could likely be honed in over time along with normalizing other variables (and including more) to improve the accuract of the prediction.

Depending on how the prediction was actually being used there could be made a strong case for one to appeal a prediction. The results are far from perfect and would be best served as an initial guideline and not a concrete solution. In the beginning, while the algorithm as being fine tuned, that appeal amount may have a wider margin. The goal would be to reduce that margin of error over time so the differnce of amount in which they could appeal would decrease.

Part III: Ethics Review¶

Whenever we are modeling our data, it's critical that we take time to consider the impact our algorithms have on people's lives.

3.0 (5 pts)¶

Write a short paragraph that addresses the following questions. No code is required.

  1. Describe one possible source of bias that exist might exist in this dataset and impact our estimated valuation?
  2. What potential harm could arise due to how our knn regression algorithm works? For example, what if k is too low or too high? What impact can outliers have? Would it make sense to normalize (e.g. standardize our values between 0 and 1) for our data points (sqft, age, basement) before calculating Euclidean Distance?
  3. Should we have an appeal process for people that may be harmed by the results of our model?
